INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1319, 1207, 456, 5, 'Aurora is the best book of science fiction/speculative fiction that I have read in maybe twenty years.  I can tell you it begins with a a girl named Freya on a starship headed for Tau Ceti, and ends with that self same Freya on a surf swept, sun dazzled beach on earth. How can that be?  Read and find out. Along the way you will share the heart aches, tragedies and passions of an amazing, touching,  irresistible set of characters not the least of whom is the AI known simply as Ship. It is Mr Robinson''s little cosmic joke that he lends to the  machine his own best literary voice. And so you will listen to the computer''s meditations on consciousness, language, free will, human nature, and even love, all expressed in a style that is precise, compact, understated, sometimes geeky, always as limpid, as pellucid as a mountain stream. At the end you will weep for the machine that has become human, and the humans who were born trapped in the machine.  Kim Stanley Robinson is quite simply the best sci-fi/speculative fiction writer alive and working today. I urge you not to miss this one.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1320, 1208, 480, 5, 'Fairly slow but interesting start. Once the action started, the story twisted and turned at a frenetic pace right up to the last page. The usual predictable love scenes, but not overdone, and the language for the most part was clean. Great story, very well written by an obvious professional.Not a bedtime story, but a fast paced and very enjoyable read for adult crime and action fans!');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1321, 1209, 480, 3, 'This was a difficult book to get into, and to be perfectly honest I would not have finished reading it if I hadn''t previously seen the Jack Reacher movie starring Tom Cruise. It was only knowing that the series was going to get better that kept me going to the end. Jack Reacher will never be mistaken for Sherlock Holmes or Sam Spade; he strikes me more of a Thomas Magnum type detective (the 80''s TV show starring Tom Selleck). I wouldn''t be surprised if that was the main inspiration as the two characters have such similar mannerisms and physical characteristics. The story was told entirely first-person, but due to the choppy nature and short burst sentences, it felt very juvenile. Too many of the character''s quirks are never explained - for example, what is with the obsessive pursuit of coffee? And too many of the flaws are never given a backstory, making it very hard to sympathize with him. I''m still conflicted about reading any following stories... perhaps when they go on sale.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1322, 1210, 480, 5, 'I''m just finishing this book as I write this. I hadn''t read any of Lee Child''s books and I had been putting off trying a Reacher book. Why did I wait so long!!?! This was a five+ star book. Holy cow, I loved it. Some reviewers have said that there was an initial part of the book that seemed improbable. I disagree. Unfortunately, I cannot really elaborate without spoiling some of the book. Here''s a kind of example. You end up at the mall at the same time as your best friend, even though she lives one city over. She''s just in the neighborhood for no real reason. Something happens that allows you to really help her when no one else would, like if you knew she was diabetic and she had an episode and you saved her because you were there. I think of that as a divine and wonderful coincidence that the Universe sets up. So, something like that happening in a novel is not anything stupid and improbable, for that matter, it''s a BOOK, suspend your disbelief and enjoy the story for gosh sake!! You will, I promise.  Go, get it and indulge!');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1323, 1211, 480, 5, 'Killing Floor by Lee Child, is the first novel in the Jack Reacher series. The paperback I read was an enthralling 536 pages full of twists and turns and, at times, graphic violence from Jack Reacher’s perspective. He’s an ex-military policeman and a drifter. In the book, he’s passing through Margrave, Georgia, and winds up arrested for a murder he didn’t commit. With no outside help, he uses instinct and his past military training to save himself and solve the murder.Aside from the author’s choppy sentence structure, repetitive use of certain adjectives, and paragraphs of needless description, which felt more like filler, I really, and I mean this sincerely, loved this book. The character and fast moving roller coaster of a plot is what captured and held my attention to the end. I admit, there were bits I skimmed more than absorbed, but there was a ton of description. If I remember correctly, I read somewhere, that an editor had actually called this book a “literary nightmare”, or something to that effect. Not to defend or praise, but every author has a method to their madness—their own distinctive writing style—whatever you want to call it, and I believe all the “editing no-nos” are part of Mr. Child’s voice. Regardless, it’s Reacher that makes the story worth reading, and I will definitely purchase the next book in the series. I love formidable characters with a bit of personal baggage and a compelling plot, and the Killing Floor came up spades with both! 5 stars!');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1324, 492, 480, 3, 'For personal reasons, I could not suspend my disbelief. I might read another Reacher book if I find one at the library.My father was a police officer and once worked on a case where he found a phone number that was somehow relevant to the case. In our small town, and long ago, reverse look ups did not exist. Together, we poured through the phone book looking for a name to go with that number. It was one of only two cases I had the chance to work on with my father (the other involved wandering along a road and field looking for a gas can as evidence of arson).In boredom, after thirty or so minutes, I suggested we just call the number and offer a story to get the recipient''s name. Dad quickly stomped on that idea and asked pointed questions to be certain I hadn''t tried this on my own. I don''t know what crime had been committed nor how dad''s case turned out. But I learned that there was no need for haste and that anyone with recent crimes on his conscience would react badly to a coincidental phone call fishing for information.Minor spoiler for the first fifth of the book: In the book, Reacher, a suspect in a murder at the time, convinces the detective involved to call the number and trick the respondent to give his name and address. The detective had no motive to hurry or be unprofessional though I could have accepted it if Reacher had made the attempt once free.The story had some cool points but I couldn''t accept the plot after the phone thing. Your mileage may vary.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1340, 1223, 462, 4, 'I finished this book and immediately went to the final book. I should have taken some time to write a review since I don''t remember to much what happened in this book. I don''t recall if things happened in one of the previous books or this last one that I am already partially through. In other words the books are written pretty well the same way that it is hard to get them in the right sequence. The author did finish the book with a cliff hanger that I had not expected.The teams of characters seem to be all over the place and even worse in time. Not sure what it all has to do with the Twins who are now separated. And where is Flamel? Like the previous books when all these gods and immortals with amazing powers meet in battle, you end up with sword and fist fights and a rare occasional puff of magic. The author is starting to repeat more and more the same comments. It almost looks like that he is trying to create another book for sale before the final book to end the story. But as mentioned before, I am on the final book to find out what happens at the end. I am intrigued about the character with the hooked hand, the Destroyer. Who is he really? Since we are in the time travel scenario, it has to be one of the main characters. But which one?');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1325, 1212, 457, 3, 'I hate not giving 4 stars to one of my favourite authors as I absolutely enjoyed and found many of his earlier books in this series (Old Man''s War) very original and hard to put down. This 6th book in the series is a collection of short stories where it looks like the author explored some additional ideas he had about the universe that he created.  Unfortunately, this book (and the earlier 5th book in this series) feels like the author is wrapping up some loose ends from the first four books in the series and has sort of "written himself into a corner". Personally, adding in an alternate ending to one of the short stories (as he did in this book) suggests to me that the author has lost his way, or doesn''t really have a vision for the future of the series. Too bad, as the earlier novels were terrific, original and engrossing in the ideas explored, with sympathetic characters and well worth the read for their originality and twists and turns in the plot.If you are just starting on this series, the first 4 books are really, really good and I would recommend them to you and highlight also that you dont need to "finish the series" by reading the last 2 books in the series (in other words, if he had stopped the series at the end of the 4th book, it would have been perhaps in retrospect the best ending for the series). I was somewhat disappointed in the 5th book but was willing to overlook it (based on the twists and turns in the earlier books, I naively thought that some of the content was needed in order to setup the reader for the next book in the series). However, The End Of All Things was a disappointment ... somewhat flippant, trying too hard to be humorous. I was expecting some captivating and original twists in what I assume is now the final book in this series.  From my perspective, there were several additional tracks that the author could have successfully explored in this universe (some ideas: setting the next story in different time periods such as very early Union or post-Union, perhaps creating a new set of old-human characters with different life experiences being upgraded to Union soldiers, the Earth soldiers being hired as mercenaries and finding themselves in opposition to the Union solders, etc), but for whatever reason we ended up with what looks like a dead end. There are examples of authors who put on hold a series for 10 years or more before returning ... they noted that they needed to refresh themselves and do others things before coming back ... and being vey successful.  I remain hopeful that the author will eventually return to this series with some fresh ideas but it really felt as if the author pushed himself to satisfy his publishers and not necessarily himself or his loyal readers.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1326, 492, 457, 5, 'John Scalzi sure brings a fresh and unique perspective to science fiction. As always, this book was not exactly what I expected in that it is really three stories, from three different perspectives, that are bound together through a common theme. This story is "The Old Man''s War" but from an unexpected  perspective.I very much enjoyed this book and if you ha e not yet read the series...please start from the beginning. You will not be disappointed.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1327, 1204, 457, 5, 'John lives up to what we have come to love and look forward to. Inventive plots and believable characters are his hallmark, in this case spanning the galaxy as we revisit the "Old Man''s War" theme and resolve some conflicts that could extinguish the human race, and forever end the idea of the Conclave.We finally see behind the veil to who is attempting to drive the humans, from the Colonial Union and the now cut off Earth, as well as the alien collective, against each other. Seems someone is more interested in returning to the old ways when everyone was facing off against each other.How we get there seems disparate at first, but he ties it all together to get perspective on how humans and the Conclave work together against a common enemy.If I have any disappointments, it would be missing the entire cast of characters from the beginning of the series, and since I took very few breaks, that it was over all too soon.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1328, 1213, 457, 5, 'Just what you''d expect from Scalzi, a fun romp through the OMW universe. I felt as though the ending was a tad rushed, since we had such a glorious lead up to it, and then it just sort of sorts itself out over the last 6 - 10 pages in an overview. But great dialog, fun characters, and loads of Scalzi''s trademark sarcasm. Solid price for a fun read.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1329, 1214, 457, 5, 'What looks like it could be the final volume of the Old Man''s War series, The End of All Things humanity on the verge of the ultimate vulnerability. Action, diplomacy and common sense (which isn''t really common despite its name) all play a part in Scalzi''s epic conclusion (for now, at least - if he comes up with an idea for another book I am SO there!).');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1330, 1215, 457, 4, 'The final story was episodic but tied to a plot line that established humanity''s place in this universe as moving forward and not being annihilated.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1331, 1216, 457, 5, 'All things Scalzi are a hit with me, especially if they exist in the Old Man''s War Universe.  I very much enjoyed seeing the story told from many different characters'' perspectives.  The author manages to make you like and care about his point of view characters quickly and with a light touch.  Looking forward to much more from John Scalzi - when will we have a new installment in the Locked In series?');
