INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1421, 1054, 478, 5, 'It is increasingly difficult to review a book by Michael Crichton, on one hand because you are likely to repeat the same things, on the other hand because every book I read is one less to read by the late author, despite posthumous novels continue to come out of nowhere."Next" is the last of his novels published when he was still alive and you find in it the tone of denunciation of his previous work, "State of Fear". At the centre of all is the issue of genetic engineering and what this could lead in the future, or even tomorrow. Around this theme a chorus of characters moves, each with their own story, a thin thread unites them, that of a science that can change the nature for its own use and consumption. Along with other technologies that actually exist, Crichton puts others that might exist soon, or maybe are already being used without our knowledge. The boundary between the two is so difficult to discern that when you read of speaking orang-utans or of turtles with advertising logos you have the doubt that is really happening, you wonder what all of this is really achievable with current biotechnology.If you are looking for a reading of pure entertainment, this is not the book for you. Nor it is if you are looking for great characters in which you can identify."Next" must be read to speculate on the future of science, and legislation related to it, to learn new things and imagine very possible scenarios. You close it, at the end, with the satisfaction of being enriched and at the same time with a sense of unease, which arises from the fear that what you read can become real and you could not do anything to prevent it.Rita Carla Francesca Monticelli, author of Red Desert - Point of No Return');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1422, 1286, 478, 4, 'This is the best of Crichton and the worse of Crichton. Ever since the ANDROMEDA STRAIN, this is the writer that rides not just the zeitgeist wave but the very edge of biomedical breakthroughs - and makes great novels on the issues they raise. The SPHERE, CONGO, JURASSIC PARK are all excellent biothrillers. In NEXT he seems to have managed the first but neglected the later.This is collection of loosely related stories, all linked in some way or the other to either transgenic organisms or gene patenting; and all dosed under the light of the human science...being, well, all too human. Family obligations, personal choices, ambition, shortsightedness and pure greed bear much more influence on the outcome of the scientific process than most scientists will ever admit. I should know, I am a NeuroBiologist myself...I found NEXT to be quite interesting, and eagerly followed some of the story-lines in the early morning hours. Yet, at the same time, there was no backbone to the story other than the cautionary message. This made the novel, at first to give the feeling of never-actually-taking-off, only to finally turn into an informative episodic collection of characters I hardly cared for.This is, at most, a 3.5 stars novel. I rounded it up (rather than down) because of the great books Crichton has given us in the past. My advise to Michael Crichton would be "no writer is big enough to totally ignore his editors".');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1423, 1287, 478, 4, 'Michael Crichton does in Next what he''s always done so well in his novels- he explores the scientifically possible and shows us how our decisions to use (or misuse) new technologies can lead to unintended, even disastrous consequences.Although a case could be made that there are enough characters and plotlines in Next for three or four novels, Crichton''s intentions seem to be to deliberately overwhelm us with the dizzying pace of genetic research and all the opportunities for both tremendous good and alarming malevolence in its application. A true Pandora''s box in that our scientific curiosity can sometimes get the better of us, the more we learn how to tinker with the very building blocks of life, the more temptations we face to play God. And as Crichton correctly demonstrates in his multi-layered novel, these temptations will not be meted out in some easily digestible fashion, they will come screaming at us in ever increasing numbers until our ability to distinguish the good from the bad is overwhelmed. And just like those multitude of spirits Pandora set free, there will be no going back into the box- discoveries might be lost, but they aren''t unmade, particularly ones of this significance and magnitude.The upside in Next: the end to most diseases and genetic defects is finally within sight. The downside: with all the money involved, there comes a loss of individual privacy and even certain freedoms.Crichton''s first question: are these remarkable discoveries truly worth the price? Crichton''s next two questions: will we ever really know the answer to the first question, and will it come too late?One misstep on Crichton''s part: the abrupt switches between story lines- he makes readers work harder than they should have to in order to follow along. But given the timeliness and importance of the story, it''s worth the extra effort even though the problem could have been mitigated by some restructuring.Nonetheless, as thrilling as anything he''s ever written- made even more dramatic by the potential for some of it to come true, and sooner rather than later- Next is a worthy read.-Mark Wakely, author of An Audience for Einstein');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1424, 1288, 515, 3, 'I was conflicted on giving a 3 or 4 star on Book 5 of the Expanse series - there was parts I really liked but others I had trouble with.The Gates are open and a rush to colonize new worlds is on and the inevitable unexpected consequences arise.  Mars is no longer attractive to settlers - why live under a dome and spend years terraforming, when new worlds beckon where humans can live above ground immediately?  Belters are fearful that they and the stations they live on will also be irrelevant and being unused to gravity, relocating to new worlds isn''t practical.  Mars, Earth and the OPA are all competing to control the colonization. The OPA has gained legitimacy in the eyes of Mars and Earth for the first time ever, under Fred Johnson''s leadership, however radical factions are gaining traction and exercising their power through  terrorist actions.The book starts off slowly as Alex, Naomi, and Amos disperse for a variety of personal reasons  while their ship is in drydock getting repairs. Naomi''s reasons for leaving are the most mysterious and she won''t tell Jim.  While its an opportunity to fill in backstories of their characters it also veers into soap opera territory at times.  Holden, without his crew and "family" for the first time in years, tries to busy himself looking into the mysterious disappearance of ships entering the Ring.The various threads of each of their narratives ultimately converge as they try to thwart a terrorist attack by a renegade OPA cell that could threaten the very existence of Earth itself.The plot does pick up and moves quickly.  A plus is that Bobbie the Martian Marine is back and has a substantial role  A minus is that Clarrissa Mao who had previously tried to assassinate Holden also is back but I had trouble buying into her character transformation.My deepest disappointment is that I keep hoping we''ll get back to the Aliens who created the Protomolecule and the Ring - who were they and why did their civilization disappear?However, entertaining enough that I will read Book 6.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1425, 1289, 515, 5, 'The best of the series so far. A page turner. Suspenseful. Bringing back all the characters I love: Naomi, Bobby, Avasarala.  First book that does some justice to Naomi''s character, though not as multidimensional as she is in the TV series. Having each of the characters out on their own, visiting their thoughts for the first time, it became so clear how much they need and care for each other. The writing is really good too. Full of metaphor, very visual. And the science is well researched, as in all the other books. My fave book of all.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1426, 1290, 515, 5, 'I got into these books because of the show, and I''m absolutely loving them. The attention to scientific detail, the political machinations, the worldbuilding, and the characters are all top notch. This book, in particular, is very well done, as we''re finally seeing the points of view of the various crew of the Rocinante, and none of them disappoint. While I''m familiar with these characters because of the show, it''s nice really getting into their heads -- particularly Amos, that loveable murderous Hufflepuff.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1427, 1291, 515, 5, 'In this book Corey gives us some character development for our heroes. Some details that would never be guessed at by reading the other books. Extremely well done. Basically four separate (almost) books. Well worth reading as are all his books.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1428, 1292, 515, 5, 'Awesome.  I devoured this one.  Couldn''t put it down.The character development is fantastic, and the plot lines are superb.  The direction that the writers took with this book, being quite different from previous books, will likely be instrumental in setting the stage for the rest of the series.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1429, 1293, 515, 5, 'best space-opera series out there and another stellar book');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1430, 1294, 515, 5, 'great series a treat to read and a fun TV serial too');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1431, 1295, 515, 5, 'Great series.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1432, 1288, 517, 4, 'After being disappointed in the last few books in the series of the Expanse, I found this one quite satisfying.  Earth is trying to recover  from the devastating attacks launched by Marcos Inaros'' breakaway OPA group the Free Navy which has also allied itself with a rebel Martian fleet that has a mysterious base on the other side of the Gates.Basically the solar system is in chaos - Earth coping with devastation on a planetary scale never seen by humans before; Mars is in the midst of constitutional crisis after an attempted military coup; and the Free Navy is exercising control over shipping and the Belter Stations.  Who else to try to bring order to this chaos?  Holden and the crew of the Rocinante - of course.The book is filled with more political intrigue than science fiction but the plot moves quickly and the characters seemed less one dimensional than in some of the prior books.  It was great to have Bobbie back.  Like the character of Holden, was uncomfortable with the presence of Clarissa Mao and didn''t really buy her character''s transformation.The books ends with a surprisingly optimistic vision of the solar system but there are enough loose ends for a follow up. I hope there is.  And I hope the follow up brings us back to the central question of who were the Aliens that created the Protomolecule  and why did their civilization collapse?  Also hope the author finds a way to resurrect Miller.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1433, 1296, 517, 5, 'Another fine continuation of the series , more of the same fun and entertainment.  However , anyone new to the series would have to go back to book one , trying to pick it up fresh from here would be less then optimal.  All my / your favorite characters are back for more ( Amos rules ! ) .Next book to be published in Dec 2017.  Many prequel novellas to book one are available electronically only ; hope they physically combine and publish them in book form sometime.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1434, 684, 517, 5, 'I''ve been an avid ready of The Expanse since book 1, and I feel Babylon''s Ashes is one of the better books of the series so far. I really enjoyed the increased amount of spaceship-related strategies. It finally gets the same amount of thinking as low- and zero-g gunfights, and it makes this book fresh.I''m looking forward to book 7. Great job on keeping the series entertaining this long.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1435, 1297, 517, 5, 'I am not sure if this is the conclusion of the Expanse but if it is then it is a fitting one. I will not spoil the plot, except to say that it was a thoroughly enjoyable read.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1439, 1299, 517, 3, 'Bit of a tough read to get through, doesnt seem up to par with his other works. Still worth picking up if you''re a big fan.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1440, 1289, 518, 3, 'Not the best of the series but pretty suspenseful. I was disappointed that most of the Roci crew provided backdrop to the adventures of Holden and new characters introduced into the series. Bit of a 2nd act slump. The theme of forgiveness is an interesting one but rushed and perhaps superficial. It feels as though there are some transformations the characters go through too quickly. And some of the action was a bit difficult for me to visualize.  Still an entertaining read. I like getting closer to understanding to what the protomolecule is and where it came from. And although the outcome of the big final battle wasn''t a surprise I was anxious to know how they were going to pull out a victory because everything looked hopeless.  Sets up the next book nicely so if you want to continue the series it''s a must-read.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1441, 1288, 518, 3, 'A bit disappointed in the third Expanse installment.  Strange things continue to happen with the protomoloecule which has  created a massive series of complex rings which seem to defy the laws of physics (at least as man knows it).  Earth decides to set out a fleet to explore the Rings - part diplomatic, part scientific and part military. Not to be left behind Mars and the OPA follow suit.  Holden and his crew, now independent of the OPA get hired by a documentary film crew to go to the Ring to film these developments. Of course, not all is what it seems.This novel moved at a slower pace than the other two books.  It tries to explore the religious or philosophical impact of the Ring on humankind, as well as what the Ring is all about.  Unfortunately, we get stuck with a rather silly revenge plot against Holden. I would have much preferred if the author had focused on the impact of humans discovering a new life form and the origins of the protomolecule - who were the originators and where are they? And what are the scientific implications. There are hints that there maybe answers to come in further installments.  So will keep on reading.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1442, 1300, 518, 2, 'If I could, I would go for 2 1/2 stars. The book overall is fine, but not as good as the first two books in the series, which were page turners. In this instance, I was captivated by the works of the protomolecule and the strange space station. However, I was not particularly taken with several items:1) The plot where Holden''s broadcasting is hijacked and the younger Mao is running around causing destruction without anybody finding out. I cannot believe that Holden could be taken that easily for a ride or that someone as young as Clarissa, no matter the connections she may once have had, could pull off the hijacking of the Roci''s system. I know this is fiction, scifi at that, but to pull of what Clarissa did a team of CSI characters would be needed.2) The Martian Navy, allegedly the most powerful navy in the Solar System, being little more than faceless goons or storm trooper clones. That was not the case in the previous book, they had more depth.3) I feel as if in the effort to please a possible PC readership Anna was shoehorned in (an eastern European lesbian minister with an adopted child, ticks all the boxes to such an extent that all those attributes in one person are less believeable than aliens planting the protomolecule 2 billion years ago). Anna is simply all the characteristics of PC embodied into one person. This is a shame, because until this shoehorned character I could feel the reality of strong female characters, such as a very human (and flawed) Avasarala in the previous book or socialite Tilly in this book.Nonetheless, I very much enjoyed any chapters covering the OPA and its characters. One can really feel their gritty trade union origin and see it on their very human, imperfect characters. The world building is certainly better than the character building. Why did the author have to kill Miller on the first book?');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1443, 1301, 518, 4, 'I very much enjoyed the book but enjoyed the earlier two a little bit more. Namely, I enjoyed the noir detective element and the political elements more than the religious and closer quarters personal elements in this one. Still a terrific read and I can''t wait for the next one.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1444, 1302, 518, 5, 'This series is like crack. I can''t get enough of it. I''ve been a hardcore devourer of sci-fi books and films since I was a kid, so I know a good story when I read it. Corey''s universe and the characters that inhabit it are what makes this so compelling. And whaddya know, the new Expanse TV series has rendered the written narrative beautifully. Good times to be a geek.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1445, 723, 518, 5, 'The story is growing, characters are developing and I just keep having that feeling of awe as I turn each page.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1446, 1303, 518, 4, 'Space opera with a bit of comedy included. I am not sure I ''care'' about the characters but this is still a fun to read series and I would recommend it.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1447, 1304, 518, 5, 'Excited for the tv series to get to this point of the story. Great character development and some good insight into more of the characters we already love.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1448, 1305, 482, 5, 'I can''t get enough of Lee Child''s Jack Reacher books. I started at the beginning and I am working my way through the series. Jack has become a favorite character and I love how Lee draws out the story but doesn''t leave you in the dark. The only draw back is that I can''t put these books down!');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1449, 1306, 482, 4, 'I like all of Lee Child''s books and have read them all,but I found this book had too much driving around in a car and not enough story.  My very favorite Lee Child book is Bad Luck and Trouble.  Great suspense and wonderful ending.  I hope he keeps writing a long time,however I don''t agree with their choice to use Tom Cruise as Jack Reacher in the movies.  It needs someone like a young Harrison Ford.  Big and strong like Jack.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1450, 1307, 482, 3, 'I was introduced to Jack Reacher about five years ago, buying "The Enemy" in Palm format, in fact.Remember the Palm? Not many people think about it anymore, because it got tired and just kind of faded away.So it is with Mr. Reacher. Here is a man, nearing 53. He has been shot, blown up, cut, stabbed, beaten numerous times, trapped in a silo with a raging fuel/air deflagration (leaving him with the worst injury we have ever seen on him) and yet he walks on.He is nearly immune to heat and cold, wearing no hat or gloves and presumably wearing the same English low cut gentleman''s shoes. He is never sick, not even with the digestive problems anyone has who travels and drinks water from a new locale. He has not seen a dentist or a doctor since leaving the army, has no physical fitness routine, eats starch and drinks nearly nothing but coffee and yet he is in perfect health, with nearly perfect teeth and somehow magically maintaining a massive musculature, which he uses to easily overpower any man, goodness, any six men, that fate tosses at him. Knowing all this, I still bought this audiobook, hoping for the same inspired style that carried me through The Enemy, Tripwire, One Shot ( a fine book brought to a bad end with the creation of a pint-sized, muscle car driving Reacher mini-me) and others. Unfortunately, "clone" seems to be the word of the day. We have near clones of characters we have seen before and Mr Reacher''s life has become Groundhog Day; he appears, there are bad people, he makes a couple of wrong guesses, he kills more people than I ever met and he moves on. By the last disk, I was skipping tracks.So, sorry Mr Reacher and "Mr Child". I wish you well as you slowly walk the roadways of America with senior citizenship rapidly barreling down on you.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1453, 908, 482, 4, 'Well folks Lee Child has done it again, I finished this book in a day and a half, couldn''t ration myself. I liked the pace of the action, enough suspense to keep one turning the pages as I did. All in all a thourghly enjoyable read and worth the money.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1454, 1310, 482, 5, 'Reacher was last scene climbing up an exploding silo in Bolton, so I was very happy to see him alive and well in the next book.  I can''t find "Worth Dying For" on Kindle in Canada, which is very disappointing.  It is available on Amazon.com but not Amazon.ca. Anyway, a great book with a bit more collaborative work than usual.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1455, 1311, 482, 3, 'I did not enjoy this book at all.  It was confusing, so many characters and unexplained, then dead.  The story seemed to drag on and on.  I figured out the hostage part about the same time Reacher did, but that didn''t clear anything up for me.  His previous book, The Affair, was far more enjoyable and less like a Rambo movie.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1456, 1312, 485, 5, 'Fantastic thriller! Lots of characters, the story keeps moving into many directions, all at the same time. I found the last section of the book, "The Facts behind the Fiction" quite interesting. I look forward to reading more books from this author.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1457, 1313, 485, 3, 'Exciting  and interesting. But can be confusing at times particularly describing the various ships and details of events on board these vessels. Overall a good read.');
