INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1464, 1288, 519, 4, 'Good follow up to Leviathan''s Wake.  While the characters veer on the one dimensional side, the plot is fast and inventive enough to hold your attention.  This time the protomolecule has morphed into something even more sinister and deadly on Ganymede and a scientist''s young daughter has gone missing along with several other children who all posses the same genetic mutation.  Is there a connection?  Holden and his crew end up helping the scientist look for his daughter and once again find themselves in the midst of the realpolitiks of the OPA, Mars and Earth and the dangerous mysterious forces behind the protomolecule.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1465, 1320, 519, 4, 'Leviathan Waking proposed a believable future for humanity in the stars, and then shook it''s foundations when it made first contact with an alien technology. Caliban''s War continues this line, and explores the further events that unfold as repercussions of the events in the first.It''s creative, realistic and fun. Would definitely recommend to a friend.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1466, 1321, 519, 4, 'I wasn''t sure about book 1. It was at times good and other times I might have left it. Then I watched the TV show and enjoyed it. I finally got this second book and have to say that I''ve enjoyed it a quite lot. I guess I''m hooked on the series now.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1467, 492, 519, 5, 'These two guys are right up there with Dan Simmons, Iain Banks and Alastair Reynolds. These have the same quality and depth that you''d expect from those classic sci-fi authors.I particularly like the sinister elements in these books. There''s a real element of horror that many other sci-fi writers can''t quite grasp. If you''ve read either of these books you''ll know I''m referring to the chilling events on ''Eros''. Ugh, just thinking about it gives me the squits.The Sci-fi tech elements are really sharp and believable to a Gormclops such as myself. I can''t believe these books don''t have higher ratings and more reviews but I guess it''s just a matter of time.I expect to see great things from these two writers in the future.Buy all of these books now if you like intelligent, hard core space opera with a flare for the gruesome.');
