INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1531, 863, 571, 4, 'Like book four, book five begins before Horus''s terrible massacre with viral weaponry on Isstvan III.Primarch Fulgrim loves art, be they sculptures, paintings, music, or otherwise. Among his expedition resides the best each medium has to offer. Things are slowly changing. The pace of change quickens after Fulgrim takes a silver blade from his crushed enemies. With the touch of the hilt, Fulgrim begins to hear a voice, calling itself the Spirit of Perfection, within his head.The Apothecary Fabius sways Fulgrim into allowing him permission to conduct experiments toward perfection. Fabius seeks to enhance the gene-seed of the Astartes. Many Astartes, such as Lord Commander Eidolon, Captain Marius Vairosean, and Captain Lucius, submit themselves to receive augmentative surgery. (This cannot be good.)Once Fulgrim joins the Warmaster''s treasonous plans, Fulgrim tries to coax Primarch Ferrus Manus to their cause. When Fulgrim fails battle lines are drawn. Fulgrim and Ferrus Manus stand on opposing sides. Only one can be allowed to live.**** Author Graham McNeill simply skims over the battle on Isstvan III. After all, it has been told twice already from two different point-of-views. The previous stories focused on battles on planets or ship corridors. First these were against the Emperor''s enemies. However, this one focuses on the corruption of art and the secret desires of Battle Brothers. No fights between reanimated Astartes this time. No, the dark forces of Chaos bring the blood and gore to the opera house this time. This, for me, is the best part of the book. McNeill brings the nightmare to vivid life before continuing the blood bath elsewhere. The book starts out slowly, but the pace picks up quickly. By the ending readers will find themselves holding their breaths and sitting on the edge of their seats. A great addition to the saga! ****Reviewed by Detra Fitch of Huntress Reviews.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1532, 1363, 571, 5, 'Best book in the series.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1533, 1364, 503, 5, 'Orson Scott Card...you are a genius.  I have never ready anything you have written that I didn''t like.  The Mither Mages series starts off quirky and ends up world changing.  As usual, well drawn characters, interesting motives, surprising twists, and a great read.  It''s unfair that one guy can write so many fantastic books...thanks Orson!!!');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1534, 1171, 503, 3, 'Interesting, but not as good as # 2 and # 1 (the best). At times I felt as if I were reading the Bible, but with far less action than the actual Bible. Very chatty, preachy book about Good vs Evil. The end is satisfying though, and all in all, it''s not a bad read. I''d read Book # 4 if it''s ever written, because the end left things open, and the situation that led to the preaching has been resolved.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1535, 1140, 503, 3, 'I MUST SAY THAT THIS WAS A RATHER SUPERFICIAL ENDING TO THE SERIES.  ALMOST A LAZY BOOK.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1536, 492, 503, 3, 'Too much like the end of Nárnia. Fun but no realm issue to be dealt with. It was Entertaining thou.');
