INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1553, 1377, 505, 4, 'This was a fast read for me.  It reminded me a bit of Larry Mcmurtry''s westerns in the Lonesome Dove series, but this is historical fiction.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1554, 1378, 514, 4, 'This was a fairly standard space adventure, featuring an action-packed plot, and a likeable diverse cast of characters, that aren’t necessarily all nice guys/gals but not the grimmest of them all either. Not too deep on plot, and lots of room left to explore the characters and the world in future novels. A nice light read, and good start to a series that I am looking forward to continuing.I did run across this book on a humorous sci-fi list. While it did have a few snort worthy moments--in the good way, not in the author just wrote something too ridiculous to conceive way-- I would call this lighter in tone before I’d call it humorous.c/p from my gooreads');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1555, 1379, 514, 4, 'I really enjoyed this. A good old fashioned space caper with a fast moving plot and well done protagonists. If you want a fun sci-fi caper that isn''t heavy or dark, here you go.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1556, 1380, 514, 5, 'The book came on time and exactly as described.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1538, 1365, 504, 4, 'I loved The Daily Show with Jon Stewart.  I was convinced that no one could replace him.  Then along came a South African dude with a dazzling smile, deep dimples and a strong comedic back ground along with natural intelligence.  So I have continued watching The Daily Show without really knowing too much about Trevor Noah but liking what I saw and heard.  Then he wrote a book.  It''s autobiographical but not an autobiography.He writes about his upbringing in South Africa.  He explains that he has a black mother and a white father, hence the name of the book "Born a Crime."  We hear how he moved from various sections of the city where he was not supposed to live.  In South Africa, it''s not a question of black or white people.  There people are known as Black, Coloured and White and must live according to their skin tone.  Since Trevor is very light skinned but not white enough for South Africa, he technically couldn''t live with his mother in the black neighbourhood.  But his mother did not believe she should have to live in the Black "hood", so she secretly lived in the white area.  You''ll have to read the book to see how she pulled it off.  He takes us through his school days and his unruly early life.  He explains how he changed from committing petty crimes to becoming a DJ and later a comedian.  But the book comes to a sudden end when he tells us about a terribly tragedy which befell him in his early twenties.Unfortunately he stops there and we don''t get to find out how he arrived in the U.S.A.  If he immigrated to America or got his television job and is there on a work visa.  If the States will be his permanent home or he intends to get back to South Africa in the future.  We also don''t learn anything about his personal life or how he enjoys his Daily show venture.  Maybe he plans to write another book down the road.  If so, I''d buy it.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1539, 1366, 504, 5, 'I bought this book simply because I love Trevor Noah''s humour and his show and wanted to learn about the man but I got so much more than I bargained for. This book is an eye opening account of life in South Africa from the late days of Apartheid to the present day (almost) and follows Trevor''s unprivileged life. It is told with unapologetic honesty, insight and humour. This story is as much his story as it is the story of his mother''s love, strength and wisdom. I could not put it down and read it in one day. It had me shaking my head, laughing out loud and crying in the end. Highly recommended!');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1540, 1367, 504, 4, 'In his story you experience the absurdity of apartheid. He never feels sorry for himself but gives factual details of daily life and events that made me wonder how he survived. Just what is it like to grow up in a wacky, topsy turvy world where there is no reason or justice applied to governing every aspect of  living. His navigation through the labyrinth of churches, schools, and neighbourhoods is downright breathtaking AND funny. The title of his book says a lot but his story is an education.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1541, 1368, 504, 5, 'Such a great memoir! I learned so much about South African life and history from one who has lived it. And Trevor''s mom is such a phenomenal person. No wonder a movie is being made about her. It will be fascinating. Trevor''s sense of the sublime and the ridiculous just shines through. And he was clearly a little hellion growing up and freely admits it. This is a great read!');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1542, 1369, 504, 4, 'I love Trevor Noah''s style of recapping the day''s events on his The Daily Show. He is bright, articulate, funny and has a way of putting a new light on our world, in keeping with Jon Stewart''s style.What I did not appreciate until after reading this book, was how hard and how far Trevor traveled to get to the Daily Show anchor chair. Why he is not dead, sitting in a South African jail or panhandling on a New York Street is in itself a miracle. His success can be credited as much to his wit and street smarts as it is to his mother. While she had flaws, her undying resolve that Trevor do things better, proper and right kept him on, more of less, the straight and narrow.An interesting read if you are a Trevor fan.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1543, 1370, 504, 4, 'While the stories are quite interesting, the presentation is highly disjointed. It reads as if each chapter were a separate essay and someone else threw them together in almost random fashion with no regard to continuity. The reader is faced with the same explanatory material multiple times. Perhaps these stories were reused from stand-up routines.Overall, the book is a glimpse into the seminal moments of his childhood. Although he never fit in no matter what crowd his was with, Trevor carried himself as a talented young man with a penchant for hyperbole and self aggrandizement.There are many unanswered questions: for example, how did this upbringing lead to his work in comedy and now television? And despite the unlucky relationships, we''re not told of the good ones — again probably because this material was repurposed from comedy routines and there''s little humour in everything going well.Despite the poor editing and composition, the stories themselves are good. I found myself laughing on several occasions. I also found myself reflecting on how I treat others. Given the quick nature of the read, I recommend this book.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1544, 1371, 504, 5, 'Excellent book. Glad I got the audio book and listened to and fro my commute to work. Trevor narrates the book eloquently and makes you feel he''s talking to you face to face. He gives an insight of South African history and culture, the hardships faced during the apartheid by the non whites and the ways of survival around those hardships. I would give it more than 5 stars if I could.I received this audiobook a week late than advertised however the supplier was very prompt and helpful in answering to my query.I''m glad the audiobook eventually arrived, a must read (or must listen) !');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1545, 1372, 504, 5, 'Looking at such a difficult time and situation through the eyes and mind of someone who is able to add some humor to it while not taking away from the severity of the circumstances.  I''d definitely recommend and am really looking forward to discussing this one with my book club!');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1546, 1373, 505, 5, 'Not quite what I imagined when I first started reading this,but caught my imagination and quickly developed into a exciting and historical adventure.The story reminded me of another great author Wilber Smiths style of writing mixing historical events with fictitious characters.A enjoyable read.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1547, 492, 505, 4, 'Another great book by the late, great Michael Chrichton!  As usual with his work, it illuminates and makes contemporary historical events from a fascinating era in history.  His pace, narrative. plot. dialogue etc is taut. compelling and extremely enjoyable.  Man, I miss this guy!  Taken from us way too early.Bob B. Vancouver Canada');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1548, 1213, 505, 5, 'It was a real quick read, but i thoroughly enjoyed it from start to finish. There weren''t too many MC books I hadn''t read yet, so finding this one was really great.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1549, 653, 505, 5, 'I purchased the book as a gift  He was very happy to receive the last book written by his favorite author  All though he hasnt read it as of yet he is certain it will be a good read');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1550, 1374, 505, 3, 'The book was interesting enough, but not sure how much of it was written by Michael Crichton vs not.  It was not as engaging as his other books to be, but interesting enough that I still did finish it.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1551, 1375, 505, 4, 'Good read! Very interesting story of early paleontology in the United States. Michael Crichton was a great author. The book arrived when promised and was in new condition.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1557, 565, 545, 5, 'This was a book that I heard of when I was an apprentice to the Painting and Decorating trade in Great Britain in the 1940''s (yes, I''m that old.)  I never bothered to read it then, but something triggered the thought in my mind recently, to try to find and read it now.  I am glad that I did.  It brought back those terribly poor days and the hard times we went through just before World War II.  It was (for me at least,) a very revealing and enlightening read.  The author''s views on Socialism were something to be concerned about, and certainly did not reflect my thinking, but were food for thought just the same. All in all though, a very entertaining read.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1558, 566, 545, 1, 'Sigh. This is what passes for a classic?A novel isn''t just a bunch of stuff that happens. And adding a couple of lame speeches does not save it.There isn''t any story to speak of. This stuff was all cliché when it was written. There is no attempt at depth of character, most characters consisting of one note. This is a thinly veiled screed for a naïve form of socialism, one which 15 minutes of careful thought will demonstrate to be hopelessly doomed. The system he moans against isn''t capitalism. And the system he plans to replace it with is more of the same system that he complains about, very explicitly within the book.I downloaded the free Kindle edition. And I got ripped off at the price.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1559, 567, 545, 5, 'I first read this book when I was in my 20''s, having just read it again in my 70''s, and it seemed that I was reading my own biography!! All of the incredibly insights of human nature Robert has written about in his book, greed, selfishness, dishonesty, evil employers, religious nutcases, I have met them all, and not much has change in the 100 years since it was written. It was like a walk down memory lane. A most enjoyable read, couldn''t put it down.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1560, 568, 545, 4, 'Poor writing which has too much "tell" and not enough "show," but is still powerful in its message. The misery of the working-class man is brought prominently to the fore, and the hopelessness of the system in which they are forced to participate. The socialist message is presented quite clearly, and the story is convincing in that the present capitalism system isn''t fixable, though the implementation of socialism isn''t as simple as the writer would have us believe.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1561, 569, 545, 5, 'A thoughtful, yet easy, read. Students of Milton Friedman will hate this book while Keynsian''s will applaud it. Regardless of your outlook, you will need to contact a friend who will confirm your bias.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1562, 570, 545, 5, 'This is a classic for the Left, and should be required reading for everybody who wants to understand the roots of the endangered labour movement. Still relevant.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1563, 571, 545, 4, 'Does a good job in personal way of describing the stirrings of socialism in early 20th century and the conditions of the working poor leading up to it.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1564, 572, 545, 5, 'A lady I worked with, a long time ago, recommended this book to me. It is genuinely Socialistic in outlook (although Mr. Tressell was not afraid to critise what he saw as ''wrongs'' in Socialism itself. This makes great sense, as no one political system is perfect as we all know.The book is based on a Company of builders in the early 20th Century ''Botich & Co.'' if I remember rightly. You read the conditions of the workers which are pretty harrowing (as working class environment was, at the time). You meet the workers'' families as well. You see the struggles they have to survive on the times when bad weather put the builders ''off work''The Foreman liased between the Management and the workers. I cannot remember his name now, as it is a long time since I have read the book.He is an important character.Some of the workers'' try to justify their injustices as being ''what they, as working class people must expect'' There was One man who joined the company, who tried to educate his fellow workers as to how wrong they were, about the inequalities of Capitalism. He was not popular for taking this stance.It sounds a heavy book, but it is extremely readeable. I recommend it to anyone interested in how people lived and worked. It does NOT force you into taking a political stance. The book is there to be enjoyed...');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1565, 1381, 523, 5, 'Unpredictable, Unorthodox, UnputdownableHorns was a shocking book. Every time I turned a page I would say to myself, “WTF! Man, did you just do that?!” The fact that Joe Hill was not afraid to do the unexpected made this an amazing story.Ignatius Perrish has suffered many losses during his life, the greatest of these was the brutal rape and murder of the love of his life, Merrin. A year later, Ig finds himself in his own personal hell.Joe Hill has created such a diverse, troubled and realistic cast of characters. Who are the good guys…who are the bad guys? This is what pulled me into Horns and never let me go. Each and every character is fully developed, by the end of the story we intimately understand the motivation behind their actions (however warped their reasons may have been).What I really loved about Horns were the blurred lines between good and evil; heaven and hell, devils and demons. Is Ig, with his full set of Horns the Hero or the Villain? Can the devil be the good guy?Horns is a book that I hated to put down; it was not rushed, it never (ever) dragged on. This is a fantastic example of book perfection, I have never read anything quite like this before.7 Stars');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1566, 1382, 523, 4, 'Horns is a decidedly strange book. It begins with a half-page chapter. This first chapter gives us the set up, the hook, and everything we need to know to keep reading: After a night of drinking he can no longer remember, Ignatius (Iggy) Perrish awakens to find he has grown horns. These are not metaphorical horns. These are bony growths extending from his temples and forming curved points.Along with the horns, Iggy has gained powers of dubious value, including the ability to induce those around him to give voice--and in some cases action--to their darkest thoughts and desires. By touching them, Iggy can also see what dark deeds they have already committed.We quickly learn that, even before the appearance of the horns, Iggy was not an average guy. Not only is he a member of a marginally famous family, he remains the prime suspect in the year old rape and murder of his girlfriend, Merrin. It is this crime that Iggy sets out to solve and avenge using his newfound abilities.With Horns, Hill has crafted a genuinely original novel. How he came up with the idea would make for an interesting interview or essay. I can only imagine his agent''s reaction when the pitch was made, most likely a mix of "What the hell?" and "Oh, god, yes!"Hills'' prose, overall, is serviceable. There are few truly remarkable turns of phrase and, at times, he is given to recycling metaphors and overusing particular words. The eyes of snakes, for instance, are compared--no fewer than three times, meaning every time--to golden foil. Hill has also, for some reason, fallen in love with the word "bowels," which pops up, in a variety of contexts, at least a half-dozen times but probably more.One gets the sense that, stylistically, Hill hasn''t yet hit his stride, that he still has some growing to do. This is not necessarily a criticism since, though his prose feels a little unpolished, he is an undeniably good writer and can only get better. More importantly, if Horns is any measure of Hill''s creativity, than one can only wonder at what he might come up with next. He is, without question, one of the more interesting and promising new voices in horror literature today.And yes, Joe Hill is the son of Stephen King.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1567, 1383, 523, 4, 'I read this book months ago, but not got around to writing a review even though I enjoyed it.  Unexpectedly, I keep finding myself thinking back to this book - the story and characters continue to evoke some emotion in me.  There are enough other reviews explaining the story so I won''t rehash that, but to me if a story still dwells in the back of someone''s memory for this long and after reading so many other books there must be something lasting and memorable about it even though I can''t quite put my finger on it.This probably isn''t the most helpful review, but this is one of the few books that I can''t seem to forget.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1568, 1384, 523, 5, 'It was both dark and scandalously humorous, with a neat twist on Catholicism and religion. it definitely a few laugh out loud moments for the dark humour enthusiasts, It''s a wonderful intregue and murder mystery! I blitzed through it in less than two days and then wanted more. I''m very much looking forward to the movie adaptation, and hoping it does the book justice. I will definitely be checking out other books by Joe Hill.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1569, 1385, 523, 5, 'I had no idea who Hill was when I started reading the book. I am still not sure it matters to me whose son he is, except I''m thrilled to see the son of a famous person become known for writing.What got me was the truly twisted interpretation of every interaction between the characters. Hill pulls you in with fascination as characters interact, then as they interpret what just happened you are slowly drawn into the spiraling wrongness born of their insecurities and madness and love.Great book. I look forward to reading more of his work.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1570, 1163, 523, 5, 'This is a great story, moves at a brisk pace and everything is tied together with believable writing and dialogue.I will definitely read this one again.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1571, 1386, 523, 3, 'An interesting read but at a certain point I felt like I was drowning in violence and guts and lost my interest in the plot. If you like a lot of gory violence relayed in great detail then you might feel differently.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1676, 1444, 173, 1, 'Poor quality was used not new');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1572, 1387, 523, 4, 'I picked up "Horns" based on the strength of its reviews and something I had read in the papers about it being turned into a film (starring Daniel Radcliffe). Within the first few pages, I was hooked - the plot is extremely fast-paced, and the characters are well-developed. This is a story about love and vengeance and the proverbial battle between Good and Evil - all with a literal diabolical twist.I think Joe Hill did a fantastic job with "Horns" - I will now go on to read his previous and upcoming books. To give extra credit to the author, I only found out about his relationship to another very famous horror writer AFTER I had finished reading "Horns" - therefore my expectations were completely unbiased.Horns: A Novel');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1573, 1388, 525, 1, 'This book was a waste of my hard earned money.  I could not finished it because the writing was awful and contrived.  I know of nobody who would talk like that.  The characters were not believable.  I read my share of bad books and I can count on one hand the ones that I could not finish and this one makes the top of my list.  I hope that my fellow readers will read this review before purchasing this book.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (1574, 1389, 528, 2, 'While this could have been an alright story, between the inconsistencies and the lack of connection for the characters it simply wasn''t for me.Rory is an alpha on Delta Squad, the medical officer. Out on a mission to save an omega taken hostage at a government site, Damien, the two realizes they are mates. From there starts their tumultuous relationship.Right from the get go there were odd inconsistencies. When Rory finds Damien, he has been beaten so badly he might die from his injuries. Damien in fact falls into a coma once he reaches the hospital. Then four days later he wakes up, says he is fine, and actually walks from the hospital several blocks to a bar. Apparently four days is enough to heal from a near fatal beating. This made such a weird start for the book I found it hard to get into after that.Damien and Rory are supposed to be fated mates, but I never really felt their connection all that well. Sure, they talk easily and they are physically attracted. But the chemistry between them doesn''t really come through the page, leaving the story with a one dimensional feel.There is a whole history with Damien which explains a lot about him but we barely get a glimpse of that. In fact, we knowledge less about Rory. Anything that could build a foundation for this story or make it something more was missing from this story. It left everything woefully incomplete in a series I gave no desire in looking any further into.');
