INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (2065, 1614, 820, 4, 'I read this book because my 9-year-old grandson was so enthusiastic about it.  He told me he had the whole series, and he absolutely loves them. It was an enjoyable read: heroic adventures set in an English, vaguely archaic, location, amongst groups of animals from the British countryside: mice, rats, badgers, moles, otters, etc. The books all share the same landscape, and some of them are focussed on the Abbey of Redwall, a haven and support for the surrounding creatures. My grandson was particularly charmed by the inventive insults traded between friend and foe, and intrigued by the various dialects (moles and hedgehogs speak English ''rustic''; hares speak upper-class twit; otters are nautical, etc.) There is plenty of action and invention, a rich vocabulary, and traditional heroic themes (courage, friendship, etc.) but all done with a light hand. I was chiefly amazed that such a very ''English'' series would be such a hit with a very American boy, who has never been outside North America; and also impressed that he read and knew the whole series (around a dozen books--and they are quite hefty books--300-400 pages).  I enjoyed Redwall quite a lot myself, and bought a couple more in the series to try out. I like the world Jacques has created, and find the stories entertaining.  The characters'' realization as animals is a bit uneven and the physical scale is vague (a badger squeezing through a tunnel dug by moles?) and sometimes the rapid intercutting of narrative strands is so rapid as to be annoying, but on the whole I think it is a brilliant series.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (2066, 1615, 820, 5, 'Haven''t had the chance to read it yet, but my nine year old daughter is deep in the book. She has to stop frequently just so she can tell us how awesome the book is.The language is fairly advanced and she''s had to ask for the meaning of several words. As long as the intended reader does not mind this, that should not be a problem.Note that though this is the book that was written first, it is not the first book in the series'' chronology. Look up the Redwall series on Wikipedia for a list by publication year and internal order.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (2067, 1616, 820, 5, 'This is a brilliant story.  I used to watch the cartoon  and the book is so much better!');
