INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (2110, 1641, 782, 4, 'Weirdly readable. OK, I view it as historical fantasy based on Old Testament myths. The tale revolves around the chronologically bent timeline of Judeans or Canaanites or what you will, warring on the until recently ill defined Philistines. This group was likely subdued by Pharaoh,  Ramases III, who then transplanted them to Gaza and various parts of the Egyptian kingdom that included Palestine. [But don''t let us interfere with Hollywood and OT adventures]. Yet, the teen heroes of Joshua Miller''s adventure battle with the Philistines, defeat the already defeated group, slaying their Goliath with the slingshot, with asses jawbones - and later, actually make a military pact with this Biblically vilified, vagabond, vestigial, vulgar people who are chosen a Judean deity to be genocide victims for total extermination. But even that anti New Testament, OT exhortation, does not appeal to the humanity of author Joshua Miller.His prologue captured the racist, xenophobic language of the OT with the Hebrew/Judean lads describing the brutish, no good Philistine warrior nation as insects etc - just as Palestinians are described today by the settlers of Palestine. His young hero was alsorepulsed by the sanguinary scriptural fanaticism of the Judean assassins, including their exhortation to him to kill the babies because they would grow up and want revenge. So, good for him.Miller''s metaphors and idioms are as anachronistically hilarious but would appeal to youths and millennials today. Or to rappers. I suppose his author''s licence is well used in this regard and he may feel the same about my own four novels hosted at Amazon.com. I also wished that mine had better fine editors so I truly empathise with Joshua Miller. I don''t know him but we share a mutual friend, my family physician, who asked me to review this work. So I purchased a Kindle edition.Hugs, John ISH Ishmael.Complaints to me at ISH@ISHMAEL.CA');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (2111, 1642, 782, 5, 'Tyrants and Traitors felt like someone took the fun, witty dialogue found in Marvel films and translated it into historical fantasy. At first I thought this would be a weird blend, but only a few pages into it I was both laughing and fully engaged with the main character, Nikolas.Nikolas both struggles when he succeeds and succeeds when he struggles. He is by no means perfect, but that’s where you really find yourself in the character. It’s fun to watch him grow as a character. Having a young boy imagining being a country guard in the same fashion a modernized version would have himself fantasizing about being a superhero; made Nikolas incredibly relatable.I am very excited to see where this series goes. I do not want to spoil plot, but the story shifts very quickly from where you might think it would mostly be about. I cannot wait to see where I think the second book will take me and how that will drastically be blown away by what the author has in stored for us.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (2112, 1643, 782, 4, 'I had a general idea of what this book would be about when I picked it up to read it. I knew that it would take place in ancient Israel, I knew that there would be lions and a giant involved, I knew that there would be adventure, and judging from the blurb on the back, I could assume that the writing would be fairly casual and colloquial. Now, after having read Tyrants and Traitors, I can say that I was entirely correct. What I had not predicted, however, was that this book would put quite a bit of emphasis on Yahweh, the Israeli name for God.Some of you may know, or may have suspected, that I am not a very religious person. I do not practice or participate in any one religion, but I did grow up in a religious household, and am fascinated by all sorts of religions (especially Shinto and Hinduism).Therefore, I think that it is important for you to know that I read this book from a non-religious-but-curious perspective. There was also a little nostalgia involved, as I grew up with the story of David and Goliath. I remember that my grandmother bought me an illustrated Bible/story book from a Jehovah''s witness, and that it was my favourite book for a very long time. I read it all of the time because I really enjoyed the nice and colourful illustrations, as well as most of the stories.With that out of the way, I will now get back to Tyrants and Traitors and firstly discuss the writing. The style is very engaging, as well as amusing. There were many times where I found myself laughing while reading this book. That being said, and to those of you who have read some of my past reviews this will sound repetitive, but the writing was too post-modern and colloquial or me. To be more specific, I mean that the writing was too modern when considering the setting. This book takes place in ancient Israel, and yet much of the dialogue spoken by the younger characters contained current slang.This made it a little difficult for myself to become immersed into the story. But I generally have this problem with fantasy and historical fiction, while it might not bother other readers at all. In fact, some of the younger readers (and this book is meant mainly for teens) will find the writing amusing, fun, as well as easy to follow and understand. I also liked that this book was full of action, and that there were few moments which were slow. The fight scenes were also well-described and detailed, which I appreciated, since I like to picture such scenes as thoroughly as possible.The plot overall was also interesting, full of action, some mystery, politics, and a little court intrigue. There is also a drizzle of romance, as well as a well-described setting. There is never any doubt as to where this story takes place. I recommend this book to those who enjoy adventure plots, ancient civilizations, and some plot twists. And I will definitely be reading the sequel.');
INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (2113, 1183, 783, 5, 'It is near impossible to identify what specifically makes this series so appealingObviously, JOSH has some talent in the scribbling/story telling dept. - always a big positive!But his irreverent cast of misfits are truly endearing - their group dynamics are credible enough torender the lot of them - entertaining in a way.I mean, something happens and you can mentally ready yourself for the fireworks betweenthe crew/team on board the PhoenixNever thought it would last, but, I am having fun reading it, you have a solid corpus of fansso by all means: keep them coming!');
