INSERT INTO public."Reviews" (review_id, user_id, book_id, rating, review) VALUES (2315, 1748, 823, 4, 'For those Redwall fans who were disappointed in the last three books (Loamhedge, Rakkety Tam, and High Rhulain), this book is certainly a fufillment of hopes! A few things that bothered me about the last books, and what improves in Eulalia:1) Jacques seemed to have given up having a funny, "main" hare in his books. Earlier ones include Basil, Boorab, Clecky, Scarum, Tarquin, Dotti, and many more. In these last few books, he started to resort to groups of the Long Patrol, who stayed in the background and never had a big part. Now the old theme is back, with Maudie more than filling the place. So that is exitement number one :D2) Readers may have noticed in the last few books that rather "cheesy" plots were taking the place of the older, simpler ones. (I mean, contrast this: A big, savage wolverine on a quest to recover a precious turtle; And a worried father at Redwall setting out on a quest to find his daughter. Big difference!) Now there is another simple plot in the old style, with a haremaid sent to find a badger lord. I enjoy that a LOT more.3) The names seem to be getting back to normal ;D Maudie and Rangval are much preferable to Brooky and Doogy Plumm, in my opinion.I gave this book four stars because a few things did bother me about it. One of them is that I don''t like that the books are now being written in chronological order. When you know that a new Redwall book is about all new characters, it''s not as exiting than if Jacques was still moving around in time. I mean, how exiting it would be if he went back and wrote a book set when Salamandastron was young, and still a volcano! Or set in the time when Mattimeo was Warrior of Redwall. Or maybe about Taggerung''s son. Or something like that. And though I like the Maudies and Meheras almost as much as the Cornflowers and Columbines, they can never quite replace them. And since the books are no longer moving about in time, it dosn''t look like they''ll be coming back. *sigh* I''ll just have to go get Redwall and Mossflower off my shelf and read them again :D The other thing is that this book is a bit slow at the beginning. But NOT as slow as the beginning of Redwall is!So, I''m satisfied!');
